On February 26, 2010, FFD/HC Maintenance Department personnel attended 40-hours HAZWOPER training.  

1.9  Planned Changes to Improve Safety

FFD/HC constantly strives to improve the safety of their ammonia processes, through both the incident investigation program and a through the process hazard analysis.  The following changes to improve process safety are planed or have recently been completed:
Â· FFD/HC reviewed its ammonia containment and handling system processes, and has trained additional personnel in the procedures for starting and stopping the systems, transferring fluids, and when to unload a system to the sump area;
Â· Ammonia equipment and systems are continuously maintained and inspected;
Â· Relief venting and area ventilation systems are maintained.  Additional ventilation and exhaust systems have also been added;
Â· FFD/HC has a hand-held ammonia sensor for repairs to the system and for emergency response purposes;
Â· FFD/HC has made additional improvements to their ammonia warning systems, and ammonia sensors are calibrated every 6 months;
Â· FFD/HC plans to upgrade the facility's audio alarm to provide better warning to neighboring properties;
Â· FFD/HC has reviewed its training and emergency response programs, and will continue to train with the Eel River Valley Fire Authority, and Eureka HMRT, and CUPA, with a joint response training event planned by 12/31/2010; and 
Â· FFD/HC has added security locking keypads with individual codes to prevent unauthorized entry into the building and process areas.
